Boil a #pot{} of @salted water{} for the potatoes.

Peel and chop @sweet potato{2} into 2cm chunks. Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{1}.

Cook the potatoes in boiling water until fork tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Drain in a #colander{}. Return to the pot, off the heat. Add a knob of @butter{a knob} and a splash of @?milk{} or @?water{}.

Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth.

Stir in the scallion. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Cover to keep warm.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Cut the @tomato{2} into 2cm chunks.

Just before serving, toss the tomato with the @salad leaves{40%grams}, @balsamic glaze{1%sachet} and a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

In a #bowl{}, season the @breadcrumbs{1%pack} with salt and pepper.

Season the @Irish turkey breast{1} with salt and pepper.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw turkey and its packaging.

Spread the @mayo{2%sachets} over each breast until completely coated.

One at a time, press each turkey breast into the breadcrumbs, repeating on all sides to achieve an even crust.

Place a large pan over medium-high with a good glug of @oil{to taste}.

Add the turkey and pan fry until brown and crispy, ~{5-8%minutes} on each side.

> IMPORTANT: Turkey is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, remove from the pan and cover to keep warm.

Return the pan to medium heat with a knob of @butter{a knob}.

When melted, add the @demi-glace{1%sachet} and cook, stirring until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water to loosen the sauce if necessary.

Divide the sweet potato champ between #plates{}.

Serve crumbed turkey, tossed salad and demi-glace sauce alongside.